  <\with|par-par-sep|0fn|par-sep|0.8fn>
    I am a doctoral student in Applied Mathematics at CREST\UENSAE, Paris,
    working under the supervision of Prof. Peter Tankov (CREST\UENSAE) and
    Prof. René Aďd (PSL\UDauphine). My research interests lie at the
    intersection of applied mathematics and climate macroeconomics, with a
    particular focus on stochastic control, stochastic filtering, and
    mean-field game methods. My objective is to develop models of dynamic and
    stochastic climate economies that improve the understanding of how
    heterogeneity and partial information operate as propagation mechanisms
    of climate change and to quantify these effects in order to inform policy
    recommendations.

    A central theme of my research interests is the role of heterogeneity and
    interaction upon agents and the enviroment in amplify climate-related
    damages and shaping aggregate outcomes. Mean-field games and mean-field
    control provide a natural framework to study such relantionships. At the
    same time, climate change is inherently uncertain and risky: agents must
    make decisions under incomplete information, which can significantly
    alter the nature of equilibrium outcomes compared to the full-information
    case. This is the motivation of using partial information in my research.
    These features \V heterogeneity, interaction, and partial information \V
    dramatically increase model complexity, motivating the development and
    application of new analytical and numerical methods, which are also a
    important part of my research interests.

    Because my research focuses on modeling climate-economic interactions
    using these mathematical tools, it is essential for me to develop a
    deeper and more rigorous understanding of how the climate system
    functions, how it can be modeled and simulated, and how its dynamics feed
    back into economic enviroment. My primary motivation for applying to the
    Summer School is therefore to strengthen this knowdlege by learning from
    leading experts working at the interface of climate science, applied
    mathematics and finance and economics. I expect that period at CEMRACS
    will help me build a more coherent and consistent basis for my current
    research and inspire new methodological and applied research directions.\ 

    Beyond the academic content, I see this workshop as a unique opportunity
    to connect with young researchers from around the world who share similar
    interests. Sharing with this community will allow me to better understand
    the key open questions in climate economics, learn about emerging
    modeling approaches and computational techniques, and establish potential
    collaborations for my future research career.
